    <section class="learning-objectives" id="sect-00001">
    <title>Learning Objectives</title>
    <para id="para-00001"><emphasis effect="bold">After completing this section, you should be able to:</emphasis></para>
    <list list-type="enumerated" number-style="arabic" id="list-00001">
    <item>Identify components impacting credit scores.</item>
    <item>State the three credit reporting agencies.</item>
    <item>Identify the range of FICO scores and state how it impacts credit.</item>
    <item>Determine what information is contained in a credit report.</item>
    <item>Relate credit score to measure of creditworthiness.</item>
    </list>
    </section>
    <para id="para-00002">Your credit score may become one of the most important numbers in your life. If you want to buy a home, rent an apartment, buy or lease a car, or use a credit card, it is your credit score that opens the door. In this section, you will learn about the criteria behind your credit score how it relates to your everyday life.</para>
    <para id="para-00003">We define a <term id="term-00001">credit score</term> as a numeric representation of your creditworthiness. It tells a lender, a landlord, a mortgage company, or a bank how risky it would be to lend you money or how likely it is that you would default or not repay the loan on time. Several things are considered when your credit score is computed.</para>
    <section id="sect-00002">
    <title>Credit Accounts and Their Impact on Credit Scores</title>
    <para id="para-00004">First, let’s discuss three types of credit accounts that affect your credit score. They are revolving, installment, and open. The <term id="term-00002">revolving credit</term> account is one with which you may be most familiar. This type of credit refers primarily to credit cards. You have a credit limit and are authorized to charge any amount up to that limit. You are permitted to make minimum payments and can continue to charge as long as you remain below your credit limit. This type of credit account can last indefinitely; hence the classification as a revolving account.</para>
    <para id="para-00005"><term id="term-00003">Installment credit</term> is the type of credit you apply for and agree to make regular payments of a fixed amount every month until the purchase is paid for. An example is a mortgage or a car loan. Your relationship with the issuer of an installment loan is done when the principal and the interest are paid in full.</para>
    <para id="para-00006">The third type of credit account is an <term id="term-00004">open credit</term> account. There are no regular, predetermined payments. You are billed monthly and whatever the charges are, they must be paid in full by the due date. Examples of open credit accounts are your utilities, like your electric bill or water bill.</para>
    <para id="para-00007">These three types of credit accounts have a major effect on your credit score. Your score is calculated using one of two main models: FICO and Vantage Score. Information is obtained from the three credit bureaus: Experian, Equifax, and Trans Union. A percentage is assigned to each category under consideration. The factors that affect your credit score are as follows:</para>
    <list list-type="bulleted" id="list-00002">
    <item><emphasis effect="bold">Payment History:</emphasis> Making your payments on time and not missing payments is by far the most important factor. All three credit types—revolving, installment, and open—contribute to this factor.</item>
    <item><emphasis effect="bold">Credit Utilization or Amount Owed:</emphasis> How much do you owe on your credit card accounts? This category is concerned with the ratio of how much you owe on revolving credit accounts relative to your available credit, also known as your credit utilization ratio: <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mtext>CUR</mtext><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mtext>Sum of revolving credit balances owed</mtext></mrow><mrow><mtext>Sum of revolving credit limits</mtext></mrow></mfrac></mrow></math><newline xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml"/>
    This is the only category that depends solely on your revolving credit accounts.</item>
    <item xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml"><emphasis effect="bold">Length of Credit History:</emphasis> This is the average age of your credit history, including the age of the oldest and newest accounts. All three types of credit accounts play a role in this category.</item>
    <item><emphasis effect="bold">Credit Mix:</emphasis> This number represents the different types of credit accounts you have, such as credit cards, car loan, mortgages, and whether you are successful managing both revolving and installment accounts.</item>
    <item><emphasis effect="bold">New Credit:</emphasis> Have you recently opened a new account or applied for new credit? Lenders want to know how much new credit you are taking on. So, if you are planning to buy a car and make another large purchase with a credit card, you may want to space these purchases out.</item>
    </list>
    <para id="para-00008">According to the article <link url="https://openstax.org/r/good_credit_score">What Is a Good Credit Score?” by Louis DeNicola</link>, FICO assigns these percentages to the categories in the following table:</para>
