    <section id="sect-00003">
    <title>Credit Report</title>
    <para id="para-00011">All the scores are based on your personal credit report. Your <term id="term-00005">credit report</term> contains personal information, including your name, address, social security number, and date of birth. It includes your credit history as reported by your lenders and creditors, including the types of accounts you own or have owned in the past, such as mortgages, car loans, student loans, and credit card accounts. Along with each account is the day these accounts were opened, your credit limit, the loan amounts, your balance, and if there were late payments.</para>
    <para id="para-00012">Your credit report also includes inquiries: “soft” and “hard” inquiries. A soft inquiry is one in which you check your own credit report, or sometimes your lenders and creditors will conduct periodic reviews of your accounts. These types of inquiries do not affect your credit score. Hard inquiries are conducted when you apply for a new loan, a new credit card, or you enter into a new contract, like a new mobile phone contract. These hard inquiries stay on your credit report for about 2 years and may have a negative impact on your scores. However, they do tend to lessen with time.</para>
    <para id="para-00013">Your credit report also contains information from public records about bankruptcy and related details, such as filing date and chapter. It includes any account that has been turned over to a collection agency, including accounts with hospitals, retail stores, and banks, to name a few.</para>
    <para id="para-00014">You can see why it is important that you are aware of exactly what your credit report contains. For one thing, there may be errors, and you may have to contact a company that has entered erroneous information or failed to remove information when the situation was corrected. You may be denied loans based on an error. You can obtain your credit report for free at <link url="https://openstax.org/r/consumer_products">Free Credit Report</link>. Often, your own bank may provide you with a free credit report.</para>
    <para id="para-00015">When all of this information has been obtained, you are given a rating. From 300 to 629 is considered Bad, from 630 to 689 is considered Fair. From 690 to 719 is considered good, and finally, from 720 to 850 is considered Excellent. The main reason that your credit score is important is because the higher your score, the more likely it is that you will be granted a mortgage, a car loan, or a credit card. While someone with a score in the Good range may be approved for a loan, someone with a score in the Excellent range, may be offered a loan with much better terms, like a lower interest rate.</para>
    <para id="para-00016">Your credit score affects more than large loans, like a mortgage or a car loan. It can also be a determining factor in whether you are able to rent an apartment or apply for a utility service. And believe it or not, your credit score may also be a factor in whether you are hired for a new job. Not all employers will check your credit score, but industries in the financial, educational, or healthcare sectors are likely to check because of the sensitive information employees will access.</para>
    </section>
